post_text: Today we remember those who lost their lives on September 11th, 2001. We honor their memories and pay tribute to the courage of all the first responders who answered the call of duty that day. We will never forget their sacrifice.
shared_text:
National September 11 Memorial & Museum was live.
Yesterday at 12:30 PM ¬∑

On this sacred day, we honor the innocent lives lost and recognize the courage of those who made the ultimate sacrifice and risked their lives to save others 19 years ago. Today, at the 9/11 Memorial, we will hear the names of the 2,983 men, women and children killed as a result of the terrorist events of September 11, 2001 and February 26, 1993. We will stand in solidarity with their families and loved ones as we honor the life of every victim and fulfill our sacred promise to remember always. www.911memorial.org/anniversary

post_text:
An update from the Franklin County Clerk -

Please read and share:

It is my unfortunate obligation to inform the citizens of Franklin County that the Franklin County Clerk‚Äôs Office will be closed starting Friday, September 11th, until Wednesday, September 16th. This closure is necessary for a thorough cleaning of the building and offices. Due to the pandemic, this is an essential step in our commitment to serve our community responsibly. Our goal is to ensure a safe environment for our employees, the general public, and anyone who enters our offices.

We apologize for this inconvenience. We pledge to make every effort to complete your transactions in a timely manner. We remain diligent in our efforts to reopen and appreciate your patience during this unprecedented time.

For questions concerning the upcoming General Election please contact our Franklin County Election Headquarters at 317 W. 2nd St. (502) 875‚Äì8704 or visit www.govoteky.com

It‚Äôs truly my honor to serve this community. Thank you

Jeff Hancock
Franklin County Clerk

üá∫üá∏ LABOR DAY COLLECTION SCHEDULE CHANGE üá∫üá∏

Central Kentucky Hauling will not be running on Monday, September 7, in observance of Labor Day. All routes for the week will be delayed by one day - Monday will be picked up Tuesday, Tuesday picked up Wednesday, and so on.

post_text:
Frankfort/Franklin County Planning Commission goes to the dogs!

Franklin County - In a surprising motion during last night‚Äôs planning commission meeting, Shih Tzu Peanut Hewitt suggested that the entire County be rezoned GDP (General Dog Park). The motion was quickly seconded by Westie Henry Cross. After an hour of contentious debate, the motion narrowly failed in a 4-3 vote. However, board Chair Sherron Jackson directed city and county planning staff to further investigate the GDP designation for possible inclusion in the upcoming comprehensive plan revision. A spokesperson for the Franklin County Humane Society indicated that they vigorously supported the idea.

Happy Friday everyone! We hope that you have a safe and fun weekend. Please remember to wear your masks, wash your hands and socially distance while out in public! #TeamKentucky #togetherky #StayHealthyFranklinCounty

üåøYARD WASTE WEDNESDAY TO BEGIN AUGUST 5THüåø

Yard waste drop off at the Franklin County Road Department will resume Wednesday August 5th. Hours are 8 AM to 12 PM. Please do not enter the Road Department office - there will be a sign-in table under a tent where you will fill out the waiver for the program. Brush, limbs, tree sections, grass clippings, flowers, etc are accepted. Items not accepted include tires, trash, and hazardous waste. Please DO NOT bag your waste. All who are physically able must unload their own vehicles.

Please be sure to follow all CDC guidelines regarding social distancing and mask wearing while on the premises. For any questions about the program, please call the Road Department at 502-875-8760.

Interested in finished compost material? Fill out our survey ! Our Solid Waste Department is working on developing a program for a FREE giveaway program for the future. Click the link below to enter your response.

üéÜüéÜBenson Valley Landfill will be open this Saturday, July 4th for the Landfill Voucher Program.üéÜüéÜ

Residents of Franklin County (including City residents) can utilize one of their four (1 of 4) vouchers this weekend to take unwanted items or extra trash to the landfill on Saturday between 8 AM and 12 PM. Voucher ID numbers are unique to the individual resident (non-transferable) and are valid the entire time you reside in Franklin County - meaning you never have to re-register/the system automatically updates every January 1 to give you four new vouchers. The person with the voucher number must be present in the vehicle when at the landfill.

üéÜüéÜBenson Valley Landfill will be open this Saturday, July 4th for the Landfill Voucher Program.üéÜüéÜ

Residents of Franklin County (including City residents) can utilize one of their four (1 of 4) vouchers this weekend to take unwanted items or extra trash to the landfill on Saturday between 8 AM and 12 PM. Central Kentucky Hauling and Franklin County Solid Waste apologize for the inconvenience. Please keep your carts out for tomorrow if your trash or recycling was not collected today. And remember, all County collection is one day behind this week for the Memorial Day holiday. Regular collection will resume on Monday.

post_text: An update from the Franklin County Health Department, KY:
shared_text:
Franklin County Health Department, KY
May 19 at 10:00 PM ¬∑

üìäHere is an updated case count for Franklin County.

**Edited to add: 2 of the cases we are reporting today are what we call probable cases. Meaning they have had a blood test showing either a past infection or active infection.

We have been anticipating a spike in our case count as testing has become so widely available, test results are coming back much faster and as things begin to reopen in Kentucky and residents have more exposures. We want to continue to urge Franklin County to be good neighbors and stay home and away from others in your home if you are feeling ill, continue to social distance as much as possible, wear your mask, cover your cough/sneezes and most importantly, wash your hands!

Updates are provided daily at 6pm when new cases are confirmed in Franklin County.

#COVID19 #TeamKentucky #TogetherKy #Patriot #StayHealthyStayHome #StayHealthyFranklinCounty
#MakeAndyProud #FlattenTheCurve #WeWillGetThroughThisTogether

Last night, Governor Beshear listed three places in close proximity where Franklin County residents can get tested for Covid-19.

Listed below are the sites for free testing.

Louisville (Jefferson County)
Shawnee Park
501 W Broadway, Louisville, KY 40211
Testing conducted Monday, April 27- Friday May 1 from 8:30 a.m. - 5:30 p.m

Lexington (Fayette County)
Bluegrass Community & Technical College
500 Newtown Pike, Lexington, KY 40508
Testing conducted Monday, April 27- Friday May 1 from 8:30 a.m. - 5:30 p.m.

Walgreens site

Through a separate partnership with Walgreens, Gov. Beshear said the company would offer a drive-through testing option in Lexington, starting Friday.

The location is 2296 Executive Drive, Lexington, KY 40505
The site is open seven days a week, 9 a.m. to 5 p.m. ET.

Visit walgreens.com/coronavirus for additional information on registering and eligibility

post_text:
Today is the 50th anniversary of Earth Day! Our Solid Waste Management Department encourages residents to get out and enjoy the day, and maybe even do a little something to help the Earth out today.

Earth Day was originally created as a unified response to an environment in crisis. Solid waste management plays a key role in making sure that waste is handled properly and not released into the environment. You can do your part to make every day Earth Day in Franklin County by properly disposing of your trash and recyclables, not littering or dumping illegally, and participating in the various programs offered by the County Solid Waste Department - including limb and yard waste collection, household hazardous waste events, and appliance pickup and disposal - programs subject to restrictions at this time due to COVID-19.

Limb collection is currently the only program that is running on a normal schedule.

Solid waste management plays a key role in making sure that waste is handled properly and not released into the environment. You can do your part to make every day Earth Day in Franklin County by properly disposing of your trash and recyclables, not littering or dumping illegally, and participating in the various programs offered by the County Solid Waste Department - including limb and yard waste collection, household hazardous waste events, and appliance pickup and disposal - programs subject to restrictions at this time due to COVID-19. Limb collection is currently the only program that is running on a normal schedule. Contact Brittany Woodward at 502-875-8751 or visit franklincounty.ky.gov/solid-waste-management to inquire further about programs.

post_text: ADDITIONAL FUNDING FOR SMALL BUSINESSES AVAILABLE!
shared_text:
Kentucky Capital Development Corporation - KCDC
April 22 at 5:05 PM ¬∑

ADDITIONAL FUNDING FOR SMALL BUSINESSES AVAILABLE!!
Yesterday the Senate passed a bill to increase funding for the Paycheck Protection Program and provide additional resources for Small Business Administration disaster loan programs. The bill provides an additional $310B for PPP loans, including $60B exclusively for lending for small, community financial institutions. This bill also increases funding for the Disaster Loans Program and Economic Injury Disaster Loan grants. House Members will return to Washington this week to pass this bill in the House to ensure Kentucky's small businesses continue to receive the assistance they require. To be prepared, go ahead and fill out the application and get to your lender immediately because additional funding will be administered as previously...first come, first served

https://kycapitaldevelopment.com/wp-content/uploads/PPP-Borrower-Application-Form.pdf

Yesterday the Senate passed a bill to increase funding for the Paycheck Protection Program and provide additional resources for Small Business Administration disaster loan programs. The bill provides an additional $310B for PPP loans, including $60B exclusively for lending for small, community financial institutions. This bill also increases funding for the Disaster Loans Program and Economic Injury Disaster Loan grants. House Members will return to Washington this week to pass this bill in the House to ensure Kentucky's small businesses continue to receive the assistance they require. To be prepared, go ahead and fill out the application and get to your lender immediately because additional funding will be administered as previously...first come, first served

Beginning April 21st, 2020 portions of Lakeview Park will reopen to the public. The entire park has been closed for the last several weeks due to drive by Covid-19 testing that was occurring on the grounds. At this time the only amenities that will be reopening are the walking trails as well as the Golf Course (limited to walking players only). These spaces are open under the condition that social distancing guidelines are maintained during your entire visit.

The pro shop, cart rentals, restrooms, skatepark, volleyball/pickleball courts, dog park, disc golf course, playground, softball fields, pavilions and ALL OTHER park facilities will continue to remain closed at this time. We will post additional information relating to Lakeview Park as the situation warrants. We thank you for your patience and understanding during the Covid-19 pandemic.

Don't forget about our Solid Waste Management Department's online Backyard Composting mini-series currently going on! Each week, the team will be diving further into composting, including how to get started, the types of systems available, and what to vs what not to compost.

All information for the mini-series will be published on the @Franklin County KY Solid Waste page - so please follow the linked post below to check out the class - and give the page a like while you're there!
shared_text:
Franklin County KY Solid Waste
April 15 at 8:03 PM ¬∑

We're about to start our Backyard Composting 101 mini-series!

First, we need to cover the basics - starting with what type of system you should choose. This is usually based on the amount of space you have available. Don't be fooled, you can compost without a backyard - or even in your small apartment !

For the rest of the week, we'll be releasing some info-graphics with common (and not so common!) set-ups depending on space availability. Tomorrow will focus on small and medium systems, with Friday showing options for those with larger yards and land space.

Tune in and join us on this fun and informative journey! The Solid Waste Department is along for the ride, as we will both be building our compost systems during this time as well. We hope to be able to share pictures and instructions for our choices at a later date.

Drop your suggestions and pressing questions below!

post_text:
The Backyard Composting 101 mini-series from our Solid Waste Management Department is starting! Head over to the page below to get tips and tricks for building your own compost system. Even residents without yards and those who live in apartments may find that they, too, can compost!

Reducing the amount of food waste sent to the landfill increases our landfill diversion rate and has been shown to decrease the amount of methane released into the atmosphere (methane has been shown to be more dangerous to the ozone than carbon dioxide!). Plus, by composting your food and yard waste, you're creating your own nutrient rich soil addition for plants in your home and yard.

Join in on the fun mini-series over at @Franklin County KY Solid Waste!

April 14 at 7:57 PM ¬∑

Court Notice: The Supreme Court of Kentucky just issued an order extending current court and office protocols through May 31st. This includes holding only emergency hearings and other urgent hearings, conducting Zoom/Skype hearings and meetings, rotating team staffing plans in the office, and no driver's license issuance. Expiration dates on drivers licenses have been extended 90 days. You will receive court notices in the mail if you had a court date scheduled during this time. Please make sure we have your most current mailing address. Call with questions 564-7013 Thanks.

post_text:
üö®‚ôªÔ∏è RECYCLING CHANGES EFFECTIVE IMMEDIATELY ‚ôªÔ∏èüö®

Due to mechanical failure at the Lexington Recycle Center, all contents of curbside recycle carts will be landfilled for the foreseeable future (at least one month), until the parts needed arrive to the facility. Residents can expect to see both the trash and recycle carts being emptied into the same trash trucks at this time. REMINDER - County residents have red carts (recycle has a black lid).

Franklin County Solid Waste encourages residents to hold their recycling through this period if possible. Central Kentucky Hauling asks that all materials in the recycle cart are bagged at this time, to help reduce the risk of loose items.

Paper drop off sites are still open for accepted materials only. Please do not bring any additional trash or recyclable items to these spots - as they will contaminate the load and reduce the value of the paper.

Please keep in mind this in only temporary. We will get back to our regular recycle practices in the future. Stay up to date by following @Franklin County KY Solid Waste.

Unsure of what to do with your yard waste that is too small for the limb collection service? Why not start a compost pile?

Franklin County's Solid Waste Management Department will be offering a backyard compost mini-series over the next few weeks to help you set up your own pile/bin, dispel common myths, and help residents troubleshoot issues with home composting.

Please comment with your compost-related concerns and questions below so that our management team can address them in the upcoming videos/information graphics. And "like" this post to help the Department assess the interest with online programs like this.
shared_text:
Franklin County KY Solid Waste
April 7 at 8:05 PM ¬∑

Unsure of what to do with your grass clippings, leaves, and other smaller yard waste items? What about your food scraps? These items can go in your curbside TRASH cart, but why not turn them into black gold for your garden or plants next year and help divert waste from the landfill in the process?

INTRODUCING - the Backyard Composting 101 mini series!

Franklin County Solid Waste (Brittany Woodward & Ashley Brown) will be publishing mini-lessons over the next few weeks for how to start a compost bin/pile in your own backyard! We will dispel myths about smells, help you troubleshoot common problems, and get you started on the path to having your own nutrient rich soil amendment to use on your house plants, garden, and in your landscaping.

Please let us know your compost-related concerns, issues, and/or questions below - and we'll do our best to address them in the series. And give this post a "like' to help show interest!

The Governor‚Äôs Office is trying to find businesses from Franklin County that can make Personal Protective Equipment (PPE) to sell to the state. Do you know businesses in OUR COUNTY that COULD manufacture PPE to help combat the spread of COVID-19?

Coveralls
Face Shields
Respirators
Safety Goggles
Surgical Masks
Surgical Gloves
Sanitizing Wipes
Disinfectant Spray

The Commonwealth of Kentucky needs your help!

CURBSIDE LIMB COLLECTION TO RESUME APRIL 2

Limb collection in the County will resume Thursday, April 2 - with the East side being serviced on Thursdays, and the West side on Fridays. Regular guidelines for this program must still be followed - no limbs larger than 8" in diameter, piles must not exceed 3 feet high by 10 feet long, and no root balls or stumps.

YOU MUST CALL THE ROAD DEPT TO BE PUT ON THE LIST: 502-875-8760.
